  "final_analysis": "In the management of relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis (RRMS), the primary goal is to reduce the frequency of relapses and slow disease progression. Beta interferons (Beta IFN) are well-established as first-line disease-modifying therapies (DMTs) for RRMS, supported by extensive clinical evidence demonstrating their efficacy in reducing relapse rates and improving long-term outcomes. While Natalizumab is effective and may be used in more severe cases or when other treatments fail, it is not considered a first-line option for all patients. Gamma interferon has limited evidence for use in RRMS and is not a standard treatment. Therefore, based on the consensus in clinical guidelines and the established role of Beta IFN as a first-line therapy, the most appropriate drug of choice for RRMS is Beta IFN.",
